[[File:Rishabhadeva, Bronze from Chausa, Bihar, dating from 7th century A.D. 37644.jpg|thumb|Rishabhadeva, Bronze from Chausa, Bihar]] [[File:Rishabhadeva, Bronze from Chausa, Bihar, dating from 7th century A.D. 37631.jpg|thumb|Rishabhadeva, Bronze from Chausa, Bihar]] The '''Chausa hoard''', thus named after the place of discovery: [[Chausa]] or Chausagarh is located in the [[Buxar district]] of [[Bihar]] state, India. This was the first known [[bronze]] hoard discovered in the Gangetic valley and consists of a set of 18 [[Jain]] bronzes.<ref>Framing the Jina : Narratives of Icons and Idols in Jain History: Narratives ... By John Cort, Oxford University Press, 2009, p. 42</ref> The oldest of such bronzes to be found in India, experts date them between the [[Shunga Empire|Shunga]] and the [[Gupta Empire|Gupta]] period, (from 2nd BC to the 6th Century AD). {{Jainism}}
The hoard includes a [[Dharmachakra]] showing Dharmachakra supported by two [[yakshi]]s supported by [[makara (Hindu mythology)|makaras]]; a [[kalpavriksha]] and sixteen [[tirthankara]]s.<ref>Jaina Iconography By Umakant Premanand Shah, Abhinav Publications, 1987</ref> Among the tirthankaras, those of [[Lord Rishabha|Rishabha]] are easily identified by the locks of hair.<ref>Indian bronze masterpieces: the great tradition : specially published for the Festival of India, Karl J. Khandalavala, Asharani Mathur, Sonya Singh, p.56</ref> The bronzes currently reside in the [[Patna Museum|Patna museum]].
Other well-known hoards of Jain bronzes include [[Akota Bronzes]], found in [[Gujarat]]; [[Hansi bronzes]], found in [[Haryana]]; and [[Aluara bronzes]], found in [[Bihar]].
