 | publisher=Benjamin Press (originally published by Oxford University Press)
 | year=1913
 | isbn=978-0-936317-01-4
 | oclc=13472872
}}</ref><ref>Bird 1893, p. 63</ref> where its early form in the 6th century was known as ''[[chaturanga]]''. Other games which originated in India and continue to remain popular in wide parts of northern India include [[Kabaddi]], [[Gilli-danda]], and [[Kho kho]]. Traditional southern Indian games include [[Snake boat race]] and [[Kuttiyum kolum]].

In 2011, India inaugurated a privately built [[Buddh International Circuit]], its first motor racing circuit. The 5.14-kilometre circuit is in [[Greater Noida]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], near [[Delhi]]. The first [[Formula One]] [[Indian Grand Prix]] event was hosted here in October 2011.<ref>[http://zeenews.india.com/sports/motorsports/buddh-international-circuit-unveiled-amidst-cheers_731009.html "Buddh International Circuit unveiled amidst cheers"] 19 October 2011, Zee News</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines/2011/10/12704.html|work=Formula1.com|publisher=[[Formula One Group|Formula One Administration]]|date=28 October 2011|accessdate=28 October 2011|title=India: Friday practice – selected team and driver quotes}}</ref>

===Indian martial arts===
{{Main|Indian martial arts}}
{{multiple image
| align     = left
| direction = vertical
| header    = Indian martial arts
| width     = 200
|image1= JasmineSimhalan-kalaripayatt-silambam.gif
|caption1= [[Jasmine Simhalan]] performing steps and postures [[Kalaripayattu]], an [[ancient India]]n martial arts that originated in [[Kerala]].
|image2= Yoga prayer by the Sea.jpg
|caption2= [[Yoga]] originated in India. [[Patañjali]], in India's ancient books, suggests yoga's goal is to help one focus, reflect upon, know and express one's highest self.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Yoga System of Pantanjali, see Book First: Concentration |author=James Haughton Woods |year=1914 |publisher=Harvard University Press |url=https://archive.org/stream/yogasystemofpata00wooduoft#page/n5/mode/2up}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Yoga with Weights for Dummies |author1=Sherri Baptiste |author2=Megan Scott |publisher=Wiley |isbn=978-0-471-74937-0 |year=2006}}</ref> India's cultural journey with yoga is now popular in many parts of the world.
}}
One of the best known forms of ancient Indian martial arts is the ''[[Kalarippayattu]]'' from [[Kerala]]. This ancient fighting style originated in southern India in the 12th century BCE and is regarded as one of the oldest surviving martial arts.<ref name="Zarilli1998">{{cite book |last=Zarrilli |first=Phillip B. |title=When the Body Becomes All Eyes: Paradigms, Discourses and Practices of Power in Kalarippayattu, a South Indian Martial Art |year=1998 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-563940-7 |location=Oxford}}</ref> In this form martial arts, various stages of physical training include [[ayurveda|ayurvedic]] massage with [[sesame oil]] to impart suppleness to the body (''uzichil''); a series of sharp body movements so as to gain control over various parts of the body (''miapayattu''); and, complex sword fighting techniques (''paliyankam'').<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ww-qCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA54&lpg=PA54&dq=paliyankam#v=onepage&q=paliyankam&f=false|title=Know Your India: "Turn a New Page to Write Nationalism"|publisher= Vij Books India Pvt Ltd.|author= Dr Ahmad Sayeed|isbn=9789384318680|date=2014-10-04}}</ref>[[Silambam]], which was developed around 200 AD, traces its roots to the [[Sangam period]] in southern India.<ref name=Raj>{{cite book |last=Raj|first=J. David Manuel |title=The Origin and the Historical Developlment of Silambam Fencing: An Ancient Self-Defence Sport of India |year=1977 |publisher=College of Health, Physical Education and Recreation, Univ. of Oregon |location=Oregon |pages=44, 50, 83}}</ref> Silambam is unique among Indian martial arts because it uses complex footwork techniques (''kaaladi''), including a variety of spinning styles. A [[bamboo]] staff is used as the main weapon.<ref name=Raj/> The ancient Tamil [[Sangam literature]] mentions that between 400 BCE and 600 CE, soldiers from southern India received special martial arts training which revolved primarily around the use of [[spear]] (''vel''), [[sword]] (''val'') and [[shield]] (''kedaham'').<ref>{{cite book
 | author=Thomas A. Green|url=https://books.google.com/?id=v32oHSE5t6cC&printsec=frontcover
 | title=Martial arts of the world: en encyclopedia. R – Z, Volume 2
 | publisher=ABC-CLIO|year= 2001
 | isbn=978-1-57607-150-2}}</ref>

Among eastern states, ''[[Paika akhada]]'' is a martial art found in [[Odisha]]. Paika akhada, or paika akhara, roughly translates as "warrior gymnasium" or "warrior school".<ref name="iakoweb">{{cite web|title=Paika Akhada|url=http://www.iakoweb.com/pakhada.html|publisher=Indian Association of Kickboxing Organisations|accessdate=9 February 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712234507/http://www.iakoweb.com/pakhada.html|archivedate=12 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In ancient times, these were training schools of the peasant militia. Today's paika akhada teach physical exercises and martial arts in addition to the paika dance, a performance art with rhythmic movements and weapons being hit in time to the drum. It incorporates acrobatic maneuvres and use of the [[khanda (sword)|khanda (straight sword)]], [[pata (sword)|patta (guantlet-sword)]], sticks, and other weapons.

In northern India, the ''[[musti yuddha]]'' evolved in 1100 AD and focussed on mental, physical and spiritual training.<ref>{{cite book
 | author=Jim Ollhoff|url=https://books.google.com/?id=a9GmhwcHTRoC&printsec=frontcover
 | title=Martial Arts Around the Globe
 | publisher=ABDO Group|year= 2008
 | isbn=978-1-59928-979-3}}</ref> In addition, the ''Dhanur Veda'' tradition was an influential fighting arts style which considered the [[bow (weapon)|bow]] and the [[arrow]] to be the supreme weapons. The ''Dhanur Veda'' was first described in the 5th-century BCE [[Vishnu Purana|Viṣṇu Purāṇa]]<ref name="Zarilli1998"/> and is also mentioned in both of the major ancient Indian epics, the ''Rāmāyaṇa'' and ''Mahābhārata''. A distinctive factor of Indian martial arts is the heavy emphasis laid on meditation (''[[Dhyana in Hinduism|dhyāna]]'') as a tool to remove fear, doubt and anxiety.<ref>{{cite book
 | author=Sulaiman Sharif|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BrttF8DY3JcC&printsec=frontcover
 | title=50 Martial Arts Myths
 | publisher=new media entertainment ltd|year= 2009
 | isbn=978-0-9677546-2-8}}</ref>

Indian martial arts techniques have had a profound impact on other martial arts styles across Asia. The 3rd-century BCE ''[[Yoga Sutras of Patanjali]]'' taught how to meditate single-mindedly on points located inside one's body, which was later used in [[martial arts]], while various [[mudra]] finger movements were taught in [[Yogacara]] Buddhism. These elements of [[yoga]], as well as finger movements in the ''nata'' dances, were later incorporated into various martial arts.<ref name=Svinth>J. R. Svinth (2002). [http://ejmas.com/kronos A Chronological History of the Martial Arts and Combative Sports.] ''Electronic Journals of Martial Arts and Sciences''</ref> According to some historical accounts, the South Indian Buddhist monk [[Bodhidharma]] was one of the main founders of the [[Shaolin Kungfu]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Cephas, Shawn |date=Winter 1994 | title = The Root of Warrior Priests in the Martial Arts | journal = Kungfu Magazine | ref = harv}}</ref>

==Popular media==

===Television===
{{Main|Television in India}}
{{See also|List of Indian television stations}}
[[File:IIFA Toronto 2011 (10).jpg|thumb|Bollywood actors at [[International Indian Film Academy Awards]], Toronto 2011.]]
Indian television started off in 1959 in New Delhi with tests for educational telecasts.<ref name=tvhistory>{{cite web| url =http://www.indiantelevision.com/indianbrodcast/history/historyoftele.htm| title =A Snapshot of Indian Television History| publisher =Indian Television Dot Com Pvt Ltd| accessdate = 1 June 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= INDIA |publisher=The Museum of Broadcast Communications|year=2002|url=http://www.museum.tv/eotvsection.php?entrycode=india}}</ref> Indian small screen programming started off in the mid-1970s. At that time there was only one national channel [[Doordarshan]], which was government owned. 1982 saw revolution in TV programming in India, with the New Delhi Asian games, India saw the colour version of TV, that year. The [[Ramayana]] and [[Mahabharat]] were some among the popular television series produced. By the late 1980s more and more people started to own television sets. Though there was a single channel, television programming had reached saturation. Hence the government opened up another channel which had part national programming and part regional. This channel was known as DD 2 later DD Metro. Both channels were broadcast terrestrially.

In 1991, the government liberated its markets, opening them up to [[cable television]]. Since then, there has been a spurt in the number of channels available. Today, Indian small screen is a huge industry by itself, and has thousands of programmes in all the states of India. The small screen has produced numerous celebrities of their own kind some even attaining national fame for themselves. TV soaps are extremely popular with housewives as well as working women. Some lesser known actors have found success in [[Bollywood]]. Indian TV now has many of the same channels as Western TV, including stations such as [[Cartoon Network]], [[Nickelodeon]], [[HBO]], [[FX (TV channel)|FX]], and [[MTV India]].

===Cinema===
{{Main|Cinema of India}}
